com.itko.lisa.coordinator

Interface SimulatorServer

  • All Superinterfaces:
    com.itko.lisa.coordinator.LabAware, com.itko.lisa.net.LisaServerObject, com.itko.util.MonitoredObject, com.itko.util.MonitoredRemoteObject, ServiceManagerSupport

    public interface SimulatorServer
extends com.itko.lisa.net.LisaServerObject, ServiceManagerSupport, com.itko.util.MonitoredRemoteObject, com.itko.lisa.coordinator.LabAware
    The SimulatorServer interface provides the interface inheritance needed for custom Simulator factories as well as the RMI indirection needed to generate remote SimulatorServer stubs and skeletons.

    The SimulatorServer's primary job is the construction of Simulators

    At present, the SimulatorServer buys you little more than the built-in RMI Activation framework with 2 exceptions: -handy collection of like Simulators that enable you to extend or build additional software for tracking and reporting at this level in the architecture -monitoring of all Simulators so that we don't have a bunch of orphaned RMI objects filling up the network.

      • startSimulator

        com.itko.lisa.net.SimulatorClient startSimulator(java.lang.String stgUniqueId)
                                                 throws java.rmi.RemoteException,
                                                        TestRunException
        This is the only truly useful method in this interface for most developers. And even having said that, the LISA Test Manager makes this a rather unneccesary step. This method will construct a new Simulator interface supporting object, the SimulatorImpl in the default implementation, and give it the name requested. Note that SimulatorImpl will only live for a certain amount of time (5 minutes at this writing) without being initialized before it kills itself.
        Returns:
        a Simulator object that can be used to stage a test
        Throws:
        java.rmi.RemoteException

      • getAvailableCapacity

        int getAvailableCapacity()
                         throws java.rmi.RemoteException
        Simulators have a declared capacity when you start them, and the have a default if you don't. When tests are staged, the capacity is updated. This method will return the current capacity.
